{"award_age":55.0,"bio_image":"full\/4445f6be20efbdc2db17db43a8145fabdada09f3.jpg","category":"Economics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1915-05-15T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2009-12-13T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/8\/86\/Paul_Samuelson.jpg\/220px-Paul_Samuelson.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson","mini_bio":"<p><b>Paul Anthony Samuelson<\/b> (May 15, 1915 \u2013 December 13, 2009) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Economist\" title=\"Economist\">economist<\/a>, and the first American to win the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences\" title=\"Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences\">Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences<\/a>. The <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Swedish_Royal_Academies\" title=\"Swedish Royal Academies\">Swedish Royal Academies<\/a> stated, when awarding the prize, that he \"has done more than any other contemporary economist to raise the level of scientific analysis in economic theory\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-MIT_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-MIT-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Economic historian Randall E. Parker calls him the \"Father of Modern Economics\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-Parker_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-Parker-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times<\/a><\/i> considered him to be the \"foremost academic economist of the 20th century\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-NYT-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>He was author of the best-selling economics textbook of all time: <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Economics_(textbook)\" title=\"Economics (textbook)\">Economics: An Introductory Analysis<\/a><\/i>, first published in 1948.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Mark_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-Mark-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> It was the second American textbook to explain the principles of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Keynesian_economics\" title=\"Keynesian economics\">Keynesian economics<\/a> and how to think about economics, and the first one to be successful,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and is now in its 19th edition, having sold nearly 4\u00a0million copies in 40 languages. <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Poterba\" title=\"James Poterba\" class=\"mw-redirect\">James Poterba<\/a>, former head of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/MIT\" title=\"MIT\" class=\"mw-redirect\">MIT<\/a>'s Department of Economics, noted that by his book, Samuelson \"leaves an immense legacy, as a researcher and a teacher, as one of the giants on whose shoulders every contemporary economist stands\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-MIT_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-MIT-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 1996, when he was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Medal_of_Science\" title=\"National Medal of Science\">National Medal of Science<\/a>, considered America's top science honor, President <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bill_Clinton\" title=\"Bill Clinton\">Bill Clinton<\/a> commended Samuelson for his \"fundamental contributions to economic science\" for over 60 years.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MIT_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-MIT-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>He entered the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> at age 16, during the depths of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Great_Depression\" title=\"Great Depression\">Great Depression<\/a>, and received his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/PhD\" title=\"PhD\" class=\"mw-redirect\">PhD<\/a> in economics from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard\" title=\"Harvard\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Harvard<\/a>. After graduating, he became an assistant professor of economics at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"Massachusetts Institute of Technology\">Massachusetts Institute of Technology<\/a> (MIT) when he was 25 years of age and a full professor at age 32. In 1966, he was named <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/List_of_Institute_Professors_at_the_Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"List of Institute Professors at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology\">Institute Professor<\/a>, MIT's highest faculty honor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MIT_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-MIT-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He spent his career at MIT where he was instrumental in turning its Department of Economics into a world-renowned institution by attracting other noted economists to join the faculty, including <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Robert_M._Solow\" title=\"Robert M. Solow\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Robert M. Solow<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Franco_Modigliani\" title=\"Franco Modigliani\">Franco Modigliani<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Robert_C._Merton\" title=\"Robert C. Merton\">Robert C. Merton<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Joseph_E._Stiglitz\" title=\"Joseph E. Stiglitz\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Joseph E. Stiglitz<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_Krugman\" title=\"Paul Krugman\">Paul Krugman<\/a>, all of whom went on to win Nobel Prizes.<\/p><p>He served as an advisor to Presidents <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_F._Kennedy\" title=\"John F. Kennedy\">John F. Kennedy<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lyndon_B._Johnson\" title=\"Lyndon B. Johnson\">Lyndon B. Johnson<\/a>, and was a consultant to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_Treasury\" title=\"United States Treasury\" class=\"mw-redirect\">United States Treasury<\/a>, the Bureau of the Budget and the President's <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Council_of_Economic_Advisers\" title=\"Council of Economic Advisers\">Council of Economic Advisers<\/a>. Samuelson wrote a weekly column for <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Newsweek\" title=\"Newsweek\">Newsweek<\/a><\/i> magazine along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chicago_school_(economics)\" title=\"Chicago school (economics)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Chicago School<\/a> economist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Milton_Friedman\" title=\"Milton Friedman\">Milton Friedman<\/a>, where they represented opposing sides: Samuelson took the Keynesian perspective, and Friedman represented the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Monetarism\" title=\"Monetarism\">Monetarist<\/a> perspective.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Szenberg_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_A._Samuelson#cite_note-Szenberg-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Samuelson died on December 13, 2009, at the age of 94.<\/p>","name":"Paul A. Samuelson","place_of_birth":"Gary, Indiana, USA","place_of_death":"Belmont, Massachusetts, USA","text":"Paul A. Samuelson , Economics, 1970","year":1970.0}